WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.400
Hello, my name is George Stagg. I'm an open-source software engineer working in the Tidyverse

00:00:08.400 --> 00:00:15.720
team for Posit. I'm the lead developer of the WebR project and today I wanted to make

00:00:15.720 --> 00:00:21.680
a video to talk about some of the changes in WebR 0.2.0. So if you don't know about

00:00:21.680 --> 00:00:28.879
WebR, it's a version of R compiled for WebAssembly so that it can run in a web browser and other

00:00:28.879 --> 00:00:34.599
WebAssembly environments such as Node.js. So this is probably my favorite quick example

00:00:34.599 --> 00:00:41.320
of what WebR can do. This is a code block with some R code in it, in this case a linear

00:00:41.320 --> 00:00:46.360
model done in base R. And if I hit the run code button, you can see that that R code

00:00:46.360 --> 00:00:51.840
is run and the results shown to you on the screen. And the important part about this

00:00:51.840 --> 00:00:58.459
is that there's no R server running to execute that code. That code is being executed in

00:00:58.459 --> 00:01:05.459
the web browser directly on this machine. This is live and interactive so I can change

00:01:05.459 --> 00:01:11.500
it. I can produce a new R code and run it to get real interactive live results. And

00:01:11.500 --> 00:01:19.459
that also includes plotting. I can plot images all directly in the web browser. So you can

00:01:19.459 --> 00:01:26.860
imagine the applications that this opens for users of R on the web. And the ones I'm most

00:01:26.860 --> 00:01:31.660
interested in are things like educational content. So interactive documents and presentations

00:01:31.660 --> 00:01:40.220
like this one and educational content, including even things like R documentation. And WebR

00:01:40.220 --> 00:01:45.540
having those tactile interactive examples directly in the web page, I feel really helps

00:01:45.540 --> 00:01:52.099
with those use cases. Another thing we're beginning to look at is the idea of containerization

00:01:52.260 --> 00:01:58.779
of an R application and sandboxing and taking some R application and being able to run it

00:01:58.779 --> 00:02:03.220
in its entirety on another machine through the idea of portability and distribution of

00:02:03.220 --> 00:02:11.339
WebAssembly apps. I am also aware of one application, one person using WebR as a way to access R

00:02:11.339 --> 00:02:17.699
on a tablet. In this case, they're running WebR in a web browser through their tablet

00:02:17.699 --> 00:02:25.339
on a device that otherwise wouldn't be able to access R. So as I say, WebR version 0.2.0

00:02:25.339 --> 00:02:33.300
is now available. The top link shown there is a demo WebR REPL application. REPL stands

00:02:33.300 --> 00:02:38.139
for read eval print loop. And it's another name for the R console that I'm sure you're

00:02:38.139 --> 00:02:44.779
familiar with. If you're a JavaScript developer, you can install WebR through NPM or you can

00:02:44.779 --> 00:02:50.380
run it directly from CDN. And the documentation to integrate WebR into your own programs is

00:02:50.380 --> 00:02:59.660
at that URL there. So let me talk about the updated WebR REPL application. But before

00:02:59.660 --> 00:03:08.339
I do that, I'll just talk about the changes since version 0.1.1 WebR. So we updated the

00:03:08.339 --> 00:03:16.020
source version of R from I think it was R4.1.0 to 4.3.0. We've changed the package name from

00:03:16.020 --> 00:03:23.820
R-Wasm slash WebR, this sort of namespace package, just to the WebR package in NPM.

00:03:23.820 --> 00:03:30.500
Makes it a little easier to install. And we've rebuilt the demo application using a more

00:03:30.500 --> 00:03:37.660
modern framework. We've migrated from using jQuery to the React framework. We've expanded

00:03:37.660 --> 00:03:43.580
the functionality of the in-browser Canvas graphics and Bitmap graphics systems. And

00:03:43.580 --> 00:03:47.860
we've made improvements to accessibility and internationalization in those graphics systems.

00:03:47.860 --> 00:03:53.460
And we're supporting lots more R packages, which I'll talk about in a separate video.

00:03:53.460 --> 00:03:59.779
Something else I'll talk about in a separate video is the changes to the developer API.

00:03:59.779 --> 00:04:03.979
And if you want to read more about that, you can also read the news document inside the

00:04:03.979 --> 00:04:12.940
WebR repo. So let me talk about the WebR REPL app. So it looks like this. And you can

00:04:12.940 --> 00:04:17.339
see if you saw the previous version of the REPL app, it looks a bit different as part

00:04:17.339 --> 00:04:25.579
of the redesign into the React framework. We've expanded the view so that there's now

00:04:25.579 --> 00:04:31.380
this editor in the top left-hand corner. So I can type R code in here and you get code

00:04:31.380 --> 00:04:41.339
suggestions and syntax highlighting all built into this code mirror code editor. The nice

00:04:41.339 --> 00:04:46.500
thing about this is that you can also save the files directly to the virtual file system

00:04:46.500 --> 00:04:54.459
that WebR is running in, which takes you to this panel here. This is the file system viewer

00:04:54.459 --> 00:04:59.859
built into WebR. It's been expanded to have more controls at the top to manage files and

00:04:59.859 --> 00:05:05.660
directories on that virtual file system. And the view itself, the component implementing

00:05:05.660 --> 00:05:17.700
that tree of directories has been replaced with a React library designed to build an

00:05:17.700 --> 00:05:24.179
accessible tree view component so that users who browse the web through keyboard only,

00:05:24.179 --> 00:05:31.299
for example, are able to use this component effectively. The console is as it was in the

00:05:31.299 --> 00:05:38.140
previous version. The main difference between the previous version and this is that it has

00:05:38.140 --> 00:05:44.260
a feature enabled that allows users to use screen readers to read the input and output

00:05:44.260 --> 00:05:48.820
of that console. So if you're doing some kind of analysis, or in my case, just generate

00:05:48.820 --> 00:05:55.339
some random numbers, the previous version of this component, those results were not

00:05:55.339 --> 00:05:59.959
accessible to things like screen readers, but here they are. So again, users with accessibility

00:05:59.959 --> 00:06:08.140
issues who need to use those tools are able to use the R console in this WebR app effectively.

00:06:08.140 --> 00:06:16.459
And then finally, the last panel is the plotting panel. So if I run a command to produce some

00:06:16.459 --> 00:06:21.660
plots, this is using a built-in graphics device into WebR, I'm calling it the canvas

00:06:21.660 --> 00:06:31.299
graphics device. It's drawing those plots using a web API known as canvas graphics.

00:06:31.299 --> 00:06:37.019
And you can move through plot history and save plots into a bitmap file or clear them

00:06:37.019 --> 00:06:44.019
directly from this page. The final thing I'll say about the editor is that you may have

00:06:44.019 --> 00:06:51.380
noticed earlier that as I type, code suggestions are produced. This is using a feature built

00:06:51.380 --> 00:06:59.179
into the CodeMirror editor that we've hooked up to R's built-in code completion engine.

00:06:59.179 --> 00:07:06.779
And that means it's context aware of the code you're typing. So if I type sample here, S-I-Z,

00:07:06.779 --> 00:07:11.100
you can see it's suggesting the argument size to me. And that's because the code completion

00:07:11.100 --> 00:07:17.779
generator knows that size is an argument to the sample function, which is really nice

00:07:17.779 --> 00:07:24.579
as you're writing code to have those suggestions given intelligently like that. So that's the

00:07:24.579 --> 00:07:32.500
REPL application. I'll move on now to talking about the HTML canvas graphics device, which

00:07:32.500 --> 00:07:39.820
I briefly showed in the lower portion of the screen. So the canvas graphics device is built

00:07:39.820 --> 00:07:46.140
into the WebR application and allows you to render graphics in a web browser. We've

00:07:46.140 --> 00:07:54.019
made big improvements since the last release by moving from the canvas API to this off-screen

00:07:54.019 --> 00:07:59.859
canvas API. So here's a video of producing a plot with 300,000 points from the last version

00:07:59.859 --> 00:08:03.899
of WebR. And you can see it's quite slow. The reason for that is because each of those

00:08:03.899 --> 00:08:09.739
points is drawn by sending a message from the worker thread where computation happens

00:08:09.739 --> 00:08:15.660
in the WebAssembly environment to the main thread where that plot is being drawn. So

00:08:15.660 --> 00:08:19.660
dispatching and handling all of those messages for each of those points separately creates

00:08:19.660 --> 00:08:24.940
a big overhead. And that's what the main cause of those performance issues were. In the latest

00:08:24.940 --> 00:08:29.260
version of WebR, it's much improved. It's an order of magnitude faster. And it's all

00:08:29.260 --> 00:08:34.900
thanks to this off-screen canvas API. What it does is it lets us draw the image on the

00:08:34.900 --> 00:08:39.219
worker thread and then just send a single message with the finished image to the main

00:08:39.219 --> 00:08:47.299
thread to be shown. Using off-screen canvas has enabled us to enable much more advanced

00:08:47.299 --> 00:08:52.140
text rendering features too. We can now take advantage of the text rendering provided by

00:08:52.140 --> 00:08:57.419
the web browser that WebR is running in. So here's an example of some code, again, running

00:08:57.500 --> 00:09:05.580
live in this slide, showing off some of those advanced text features. The biggest benefit of

00:09:05.580 --> 00:09:13.020
this is probably that WebR now supports much better international scripts when plotting.

00:09:13.020 --> 00:09:18.219
So you can see there's some Arabic text here, some Hebrew and some Japanese. And they're all

00:09:18.219 --> 00:09:25.580
handled automatically now by the WebR canvas graphics device. That font fallback that enables

00:09:25.580 --> 00:09:30.859
this also allows you to use emoji in your plot should you want to. The nice thing about the

00:09:30.859 --> 00:09:35.820
canvas graphics device is because we're relying on the web browser to plot and to draw those

00:09:35.820 --> 00:09:39.979
graphics, we can actually use font files that are installed on the user's machine. We can use

00:09:39.979 --> 00:09:45.179
system fonts. So here, for example, I have family future as the title, but I can change that. I can

00:09:45.179 --> 00:09:52.940
say if I wanted to. And this provides not only a benefit to internationalization for all those

00:09:52.940 --> 00:09:58.140
alternative scripts, but also accessibility, because there exists some fonts that are designed

00:09:58.140 --> 00:10:05.260
to help users with reading barriers such as dyslexia to be able to comfortably read text.

00:10:05.260 --> 00:10:12.460
So there's open dyslexic is such a font. You can see that if I re-render that image,

00:10:12.460 --> 00:10:19.099
that font is now being used for the title and the X and Y labels. So those users who prefer

00:10:19.099 --> 00:10:24.299
to read text with that font are now able to do so in WebR should they wish.

00:10:27.260 --> 00:10:31.419
In addition to the canvas graphics device, WebR also has updates to

00:10:33.099 --> 00:10:39.739
support the standard bitmap graphics devices built into R. So if you're running

00:10:39.739 --> 00:10:43.659
in a browser that doesn't have a, if you're running an environment that's not a web browser,

00:10:43.659 --> 00:10:49.020
such as node server side, or you're running R code that isn't aware of the canvas graphics device,

00:10:49.260 --> 00:10:54.299
you can now do so with WebR. So here I have an example that this is just loading WebR into the

00:10:54.299 --> 00:11:01.419
page. And then there's some R plotting code here, writing a PNG to the virtual file system.

00:11:02.380 --> 00:11:06.380
And once that PNG has been written to the virtual file system with WebR,

00:11:06.380 --> 00:11:12.219
there are a file system APIs that let you read that file into a JavaScript variable. And once

00:11:12.219 --> 00:11:17.099
you have that data in JavaScript, you can do what you need to do with it. You can offer it to the

00:11:17.099 --> 00:11:21.739
user as a download, you can display it in the page, or if you're running server side, you could

00:11:21.739 --> 00:11:28.940
send that data over the network. The way this works is that we've compiled the Cairo graphics

00:11:28.940 --> 00:11:35.020
library and Pango text layout engine to WebAssembly as part of the WebR build process.

00:11:35.900 --> 00:11:41.739
And by compiling those libraries to WebAssembly and linking them in, we can enable those advanced

00:11:41.739 --> 00:11:46.700
text features that I already talked about for the built-in graphics devices, as well as the canvas

00:11:46.700 --> 00:11:54.460
graphics device. The main difference between the two is that for built-in Cairo graphics with

00:11:54.460 --> 00:12:00.460
PNG, for example, those fonts can't be read off the user's file system. And instead, they must be

00:12:00.460 --> 00:12:07.419
provided to Cairo through the WebR virtual file system. So WebR ships with a minimal selection

00:12:07.419 --> 00:12:13.260
of Noto fonts. But if you do have other requirements for different scripts or different font

00:12:13.260 --> 00:12:19.260
typefaces, you can upload those fonts to the virtual file system. And WebR has been configured

00:12:19.260 --> 00:12:27.099
to search that directory, home, web, user, fonts, for font files, and use them. So here's an example,

00:12:27.099 --> 00:12:31.580
very similar to the previous example I showed you. The only difference is this time it's creating a

00:12:31.580 --> 00:12:37.580
PNG file instead of displaying it in a browser. And you can see the results are very, very similar.

00:12:37.580 --> 00:12:43.099
And all those text features that I talked about, things like ligatures in Arabic text and the font

00:12:43.099 --> 00:12:49.020
fallback for different glyphs, they're all supported, including the right-to-left text and

00:12:50.219 --> 00:12:57.580
various other features. This works in this example because I've uploaded some fonts for those

00:12:57.580 --> 00:13:03.340
alternative scripts to the virtual file system in the correct place, and WebR has automatically

00:13:03.340 --> 00:13:10.859
then used them to produce this plot. So the last thing I want to talk about in this video

00:13:10.859 --> 00:13:15.500
is something we're calling the lazy virtual file system. So everything I've shown you so far comes

00:13:15.500 --> 00:13:22.859
with a price. Increased web assembly, download size, data size. If you're bundling fonts,

00:13:22.859 --> 00:13:28.299
they'll have to be downloaded. But not every user will want all of those features. Not every user

00:13:28.299 --> 00:13:32.460
will want to use Cairo graphics and download those font files. Some people will just want

00:13:32.460 --> 00:13:39.260
to do some computation and return some numbers. The same thing applies to files built into R already.

00:13:39.260 --> 00:13:46.059
So R ships with lots of documentation and examples and data sets, and they're not necessarily

00:13:46.059 --> 00:13:52.219
needed for every user. So it would be nice if WebR only downloaded the data it actually needs

00:13:52.780 --> 00:14:01.340
to run your R code. And WebR 0.2.0 does just that. It uses an API provided by inscription

00:14:01.419 --> 00:14:09.580
for their file system environment that allows the file system to only download the files

00:14:09.580 --> 00:14:14.700
when they're requested. So here in this example, I'll just open the dev tools and you'll see exactly

00:14:14.700 --> 00:14:21.340
what I mean. So if I refresh the page, you can see the R files are downloaded to run R and its

00:14:21.340 --> 00:14:29.260
base packages. But then if I run the command png to use Cairo graphics to build a bitmap graphics

00:14:29.979 --> 00:14:36.140
image, you can see it's only at that point that those Cairo libraries are downloaded to the

00:14:36.140 --> 00:14:44.780
device. And a similar thing, if I plot something now and I draw some text, you'll see that the

00:14:44.780 --> 00:14:51.500
font files are only downloaded at the point of actually producing that plot. So if I don't use

00:14:51.500 --> 00:14:57.020
Cairo graphics and produce a plot that requires those fonts, they won't be downloaded by the user.

00:14:57.739 --> 00:15:01.820
That's really nice because it reduces the initial download size of WebR by a lot.

00:15:02.940 --> 00:15:09.340
For the application that I've been showing, the demo REPL app in the previous version of WebR with

00:15:09.340 --> 00:15:15.739
less features, that was 40 megabytes of download. In the new version, it's only 9.5 megabytes and

00:15:15.739 --> 00:15:22.140
that's with the extra features. So that's only 23% of the previous download size. So that's a

00:15:22.140 --> 00:15:31.179
really good improvement for the download size of an initial WebR loading of the engine into a page.

00:15:32.780 --> 00:15:40.219
So that's everything I wanted to talk about in this video. Do try out the app and run your own

00:15:40.219 --> 00:15:45.260
R scripts. And if you're a developer, as I said, you can install WebR from npm or CDN.

00:15:45.820 --> 00:15:51.820
And the documentation is shown there on the screen at that URL. Do go and read the documentation if

00:15:51.820 --> 00:15:56.299
you want to try WebR in your own applications, because there are some subtleties when it comes to

00:15:57.340 --> 00:16:02.299
when it comes to putting those applications on the web. If you do create something interesting

00:16:02.299 --> 00:16:08.700
with WebR, please let me know. My email address is shown on the screen and I'd love to hear about it.

00:16:08.700 --> 00:16:11.099
And thank you very much for listening.

